{{Infobox organization | name = American Union of Decorative Artists and Craftsmen (AUDAC) | native_name = | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = An 1930 advertisement for AUDAC and its designers | abbreviation = AUDAC | formation = 1928<!-- e.g. use {{start date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} --> | founder = [[Paul T. Frankl]] | extinction = early 1930s<!-- e.g. use {{end date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | merger = | type = | status = Defunct | purpose = To encourage modern design and decorative arts in the United States | headquarters = | location = New York, New York | coords = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LON|display=inline,title}} --> | region = United States | services = | products = | methods = | fields = | membership = | membership_year = | language = | owner = <!-- or | owners = --> | sec_gen = | leader_title = | main_organ = }}
The '''American Union of Decorative Artists and Craftsmen (AUDAC)''' was an American society of designers and decorative artists that was active from 1928 until the early 1930s. The group aimed to bring modern principles of design, such as those promoted in Europe by the [[Wiener Werkstätte]] and the [[Bauhaus]], to decorative arts in the United States.
==History==
The modernist furniture designer [[Paul T. Frankl]] immigrated from Vienna to New York in 1914.<ref>{{cite book|ref=Wilson|last=Wilson|first=Richard Guy|chapter=Art Deco in the USA |title=Grove Art Online|date=2015|publisher=Oxford University Press |url=https://doi.org/10.1093/gao/9781884446054.article.T2283819 |accessdate=2018-04-06 }}</ref> He worked to establish Europe's flourishing principles of contemporary design in the United States by writing books such as ''New Dimensions: The Decorative Arts of Today'' <ref>{{cite book| last=Frankl| first=Paul Theodore |date=1028 |title=New Dimensions: The Decorative Arts of Today in Words and Pictures |url=http://www.worldcat.org/title/new-dimensions-the-decorative-arts-of-today-in-words-pictures/oclc/299341249 | publisher=New York, Payson Clarke}}</ref> and by establishing a collective of fellow designers called the American Union of Decorative Artists and Craftsmen (AUDAC) in 1928.<ref>{{cite book|ref=Wilson|last=Wilson|first=Richard Guy|chapter=Art Deco in the USA |title=Grove Art Online|date=2015|publisher=Oxford University Press |url=https://doi.org/10.1093/gao/9781884446054.article.T2283819 |accessdate=2018-04-06 }}</ref> Early members included designers who exhibited at the American Designers' Gallery, which showed interiors and furnishings designed by contemporary New York designers, such as [[Donald Deskey]] and [[Ilonka Karasz]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metmuseum.org/toah/hd/dsgn2/hd_dsgn2.htm |author=Heilbrunn Timeline of Art History |year=2018|title=Design, 1925-50|publisher=The Metropolitan Museum of Art|accessdate=2018-04-10}}</ref>
AUDAC was modeled on European decorative arts societies such as the [[Société des Artistes Décorateurs]] in France. They published books on the new American design such as ''Modern American Design''<ref>*{{cite book|author=American Union of Decorative Artists and Craftsmen, Robert L. Leonard, and C. Adolph Glassgold|title=Modern American Design |date=1933|publisher=New York, Ives Washburn|url=http://www.worldcat.org/title/modern-american-design/oclc/1251649}}</ref> and ''Annual of American Design''<ref>{{cite book|author=American Union of Decorative Artists and Craftsmen|title=Annual of American Design |date=1931|publisher=New York, Ives Washburn|url=http://www.worldcat.org/title/annual-of-american-design-1931/oclc/1251637}}</ref> and put together influential exhibitions of their members' work, including one at the Brooklyn Museum in 1931 which showed work by [[Russel Wright]], [[Ruth Reeves]], and [[Rockwell Kent]] among many others.<ref>*{{cite journal |last1=Susswein |first1=Rita |last2=Whitehead |first2=Philip |date=1931 |title=The AUDAC Exhibition at the Brooklyn Museum |jstor=770529 |journal=Parnassus |volume= 3 |issue= 5 |pages=14–15 |doi=10.2307/770529 }}</ref>
The group was well known by the early 1930s when [[Radio City Music Hall]] commissioned [[Donald Deskey]] and other AUDAC members to design the fabrics, textiles, and furnishings for the interior.<ref>*{{cite web| url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/0995.pdf | author=New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission | date=1978 | title=RADIO CITY MUSIC HALL| access-date=2018-04-10}}</ref> Many members (see list below) went on long careers and well-known places in the history of twentieth-century design. However, due to the 1930s economic depression, the formal association was defunct by 1934.<ref>*{{cite book|last=Woodham | first=Jonathan M. |title=A Dictionary of Modern Design |url=http://www.oxfordreference.com/view/10.1093/acref/9780192800978.001.0001/acref-9780192800978-e-28 |chapter=American Union of Decorative Artists and Craftsmen |publisher=Oxford University Press |year= 2016 |isbn=9780191726767 |accessdate=2018-04-06 }}</ref>
==Mission==
AUDAC placed an ad in a supplement for the magazine ''Creative Art'' in March 1930<ref>*{{cite web| url=https://socalarchhistory.blogspot.com/2010/08/ | title=Foundations of Los Angeles Modernism: Richard Neutra's Mod Squad |publisher=Southern California Architectural History |last=Crosse |first=John |date=2010|access-date=2018-04-10}}</ref> which listed contact information for many of its members and described the mission of the American Union of Decorative Artists and Craftsmen thus:
{{Quote |text=AUDAC stands convinced that contemporary life demands an appropriate setting and that it is the work of the artist of all ages to mould the external world to suit the life of his time.
AUDAC realizes that the cultural contribution of an era is as clearly reflected in the decorative as in the other arts.
AUDAC was founded to give these convictions organized aid and voice.
AUDAC stands for: The advancement of the new tendencies in the decorative, industrial and applied arts. The elevation of standards in contemporary design. The development of STYLE rather than styles. }}
==Founders and members== Founded by [[Paul T. Frankl]] in 1928.
Members included: {{colbegin}} * [[Mehemed Fehmy Agha|M. F. Agha]] * [[Richard F. Bach]] * [[Lucian Bernhard]] * M. D. C. Crawford * [[Donald Deskey]] * Alice Donaldson * [[Hugh Ferriss]] * [[Norman Bel Geddes]] * C. Adolph Glassgold * Wolfgang and [[Pola Stout|Pola Hoffmann]] * Ellen M. Kern * [[Frederick John Kiesler]] * Peter Larsen * Robert Leonard * [[Marguerita Mergentime]] * [[Lewis Mumford]] * [[Ruth Reeves]] * [[Winold Reiss]] * Robert Schey * [[Lee Simonson]] * [[Edward Steichen]] * [[Edward Buk Ulreich]] * [[Kem Weber]] * [[Frank Lloyd Wright]] * [[Russel Wright]] * Paul M. Zimmermann {{colend}}
