{{Infobox tractor |name = Bucyrus Erie Model 1850-B "Brutus" |image = Brutus 2006-07-02 2244.jpg |caption = Note humans by track for scale |manufacturer = Bucyrus-Erie |production = 1 unit made; June 1962 to May 1963 at a cost of $6.5 million |length = {{convert|79.5|ft|m}} (house) |width = {{convert|58|ft|m}} (house) |height = {{convert|160|ft|m|1}} (to tip of boom) |weight = {{convert|9300000|lb|kg}} + {{convert|1700000|lb|kg}} ballast when operational |propulsion = Caterpillar tracks |speed = 0.22 mph (19 ft/min) (5.8m/min) max |type = Electric shovel |gross_power = ≥7,500 hp (standard), ≥15,000 hp (peak) |blade_capacity = {{convert|90|cuyd|m3|1}} or {{convert|150|ST|t}} | engine_model = | flywheel_power = | drawbar_pull =}}
'''''Big Brutus''''' is the nickname of the [[Bucyrus-Erie]] model 1850-B electric [[Power shovel|shovel]], which was the second largest of its type in operation in the 1960s and 1970s. Big Brutus is the centerpiece of a mining museum in [[West Mineral, Kansas]] where it was used in coal [[strip mining]] operations. The shovel was designed to dig from {{convert|20|to|69|ft|m}}<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://files.asme.org/ASMEORG/Communities/History/Landmarks/5504.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-03-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100703023704/http://files.asme.org/ASMEORG/Communities/History/Landmarks/5504.pdf |archive-date=2010-07-03 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref> down to unearth relatively shallow coal seams, which would themselves be mined with smaller equipment.
==Description== Fabrication of Big Brutus was completed in May 1963, after which it was shipped in 150 railroad cars to be assembled in Kansas. It operated until 1974, when it became uneconomical to mine coal at the site. At that time it was considered too big to move and was left in place.
Big Brutus, while not the largest electric shovel ever built, is the largest electric shovel still in existence. [[Marion 6360|The Captain]], at 28 million pounds &ndash; triple that of Big Brutus &ndash; was the largest shovel and one of the largest land-based mobile machines ever built, only exceeded by some [[dragline excavator|dragline]] and [[bucket-wheel excavator]]s. It was scrapped in 1992, after receiving extreme damage from an hours-long internal fire.<ref name="col">{{cite book|last=Haddock|first=Keith|title=Colossal Earthmovers|publisher=MBI|date=September 18, 2000|pages=67|isbn=978-0-7603-0771-7}}</ref>
==Museum== The Pittsburg & Midway Coal Mining Company donated Big Brutus in 1984 as the core of a mining museum which opened in 1985. In 1987, the [[American Society of Mechanical Engineers]] designated Big Brutus a Regional Historic Mechanical Engineering Landmark.<ref name="about">{{cite web|url=http://www.bigbrutus.org/about.html|title=About Big Brutus|publisher=Big Brutus, Inc.|accessdate=2009-07-19}}</ref> It was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 2018.
The museum offers tours and camping.
